n| board_of_directors  = \n| key_people          = \n| main_organ          = \n| parent_organization = \n| subsidiaries        = \n| secessions          = \n| affiliations        = \n| budget              = \n| budget_year         = \n| revenue             = \n| revenue_year        = \n| disbursements       = \n| expenses            = \n| expenses_year       = \n| endowment           = \n| staff               = \n| staff_year          = \n| volunteers          = \n| volunteers_year     = \n| slogan              = \n| mission             = \n| website             = {{Official URL}}\n| remarks             = \n| formerly            = \n| footnotes           = \n}}\n\nThe '''Open Geospatial Consortium''' ('''OGC'''), an international voluntary consensus [[standards organization]], originated in 1994. In the OGC, more than 500 commercial, governmental, nonprofit and research organizations worldwide collaborate in a consensus process encouraging development and implementation of open standards for [[geospatial]] content and services, sensor web and [[Internet of Things]], [[Geographic information system|GIS]] [[data processing]] and [[data sharing]].\n\n==History==\nA predecessor organization, OGF, the Open [[GRASS GIS|GRASS]] Foundation, started in 1992.<ref>[http://gisws.media.osaka-cu.ac.jp/grass04/viewpaper.php?id=53 ''GRASS Roots''], Westervelt, p. 5</ref>\n\nFrom 1994 to 2004 the organization also used the name '''Open GIS Consortium'''.\n\nThe OGC website gives a detailed history of the OGC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ogc.org/ogc/historylong|title=OGC History (detailed) &#124; OGC|website=www.ogc.org}}</ref>\n\n== Standards ==\nMost of the OGC standards depend on a generalized architecture captured in a set of documents collectively called the ''Abstract Specification'', which describes a basic data model for representing [[geographic]] features. Atop the Abstract Specification members have developed and continue to develop a growing number of specifications, or [[standardization|''standards'']] to serve specific needs for [[interoperability|interoperable]] location and geospatial technology, including GIS.\n\nMore information here: [http://www.opengeospatial.org/standards OGC\u00ae Standards and Supporting Documents | OGC]\n\n[[File:GeoServer GeoNetwork with web app.svg|thumb|347px|Relationship between clients/servers and OGC protocols]]\n\nThe OGC standards baseline comprises more than 30 standards,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ogc.org/standards/|title=OGC\u00ae Standards and Supporting Documents &#124; OGC|website=www.ogc.org}}</ref> including:\n\n* 3D Tiles \u2013 Designed for streaming and rendering massive 3D geospatial content such as Photogrammetry, 3D Buildings, BIM/CAD, Instanced Features, and Point Clouds. \n*[[Catalog Service for the Web|CSW]] \u2013 Catalog Service for the Web: access to catalog information\n*[[Geography Markup Language|GML]] \u2013 Geography Markup Language: [[XML]]-format for geographical information\n*[[GeoXACML]] \u2013 Geospatial eXtensible Access Control Markup Language\n*[[Keyhole Markup Language|KML]] \u2013 [[Keyhole, Inc|Keyhole]] Markup Language: [[XML]]-based language schema for expressing geographic annotation and visualization on existing (or future) Web-based, two-dimensional maps and three-dimensional Earth browsers\n*[[Observations and Measurements]]\n*[[OGC Reference Model]] \u2013 a complete set of [[Reference Model|reference models]]\n*[[Location Service (OpenLS)|OLS]] \u2013 Open Location Service (OpenLS)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opengeospatial.org/standards/ols|title=OGC Standard \u2013 Location Service|year=2017|accessdate=2017-02-01}}</ref>\n*[[OWS Context|OGC Web Services Context Document]] defines the application state of an OGC Integrated Client \n*[[Web Service Common|OWS]] \u2013 OGC Web Service Common\n*[[Sensor Observation Service|SOS]] \u2013 Sensor Observation Service<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opengeospatial.org/standards/sos|title=OGC Standard \u2013 Sensor Observation Service|year=2008|accessdate=2008-10-29}}</ref>\n*SPS \u2013 Sensor Planning Service<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opengeospatial.org/standards/sps|title=OGC Standard \u2013 Sensor Planning Service|year=2010|accessdate=2010-04-14}}</ref>\n*[[SensorML]] \u2013 Sensor Model Language\n*[[SensorThings API]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opengeospatial.org/projects/groups/sensorthings|title=OGC Standard \u2013 SensorThings API|year=2015|accessdate=2015-11-03}}</ref> - an open and unified framework to interconnect IoT devices, data, and applications over the Web. Currently a candidate standard waiting for votes.\n*[[Simple Features|SFS]] \u2013 Simple Features \u2013 SQL\n*[[Styled Layer Descriptor|SLD]] - Styled Layer Descriptor\n*[[SRID]], an identification for spatial coordinate systems \n*[[WaterML]] \u2013 Information model for the representation of hydrological observation data\n*[[Web Coverage Service|WCS]] \u2013 Web Coverage Service: provides access, subsetting, and processing on [[Coverage data|coverage objects]]\n*[[Web Coverage Processing Service|WCPS]] \u2013 Web Coverage Processing Service: provides a raster query language for ad-hoc processing and filtering on raster [[Coverage data|coverages]]\n*[[Web Feature Service|WFS]] \u2013 Web Feature Service: for retrieving or altering feature descriptions\n*[[Web Map Service|WMS]] \u2013 Web Map Service: provides map images\n*[[Web Map Tile Service|WMTS]] \u2013 Web Map Tile Service: provides map image tiles\n*[[Web Processing Service|WPS]] \u2013 Web Processing Service: remote processing service\n*[[GeoSPARQL]] \u2013 Geographic SPARQL Protocol and RDF Query Language:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opengeospatial.org/standards/geosparql|title=GeoSPARQL \u2013 A Geographic Query Language for RDF Data|accessdate=2012-11-25}}</ref> representation and querying of geospatial data for the [[Semantic Web]]\n*[[Web Terrain Service|WTS]] \u2013 Web Terrain Service (WTS)\n\nThe design of standards were originally built on the [[HTTP]] web services [[paradigm]] for message-based interactions in web-based systems, but meanwhile has been extended with a common approach for [[SOAP (protocol)|SOAP]] protocol and [[Web Services Description Language|WSDL]] bindings. Considerable progress has been made in defining [[Representational State Transfer]] (REST) web services, e.g., OGC [[SensorThings API]].\n\n==Organization structure==\nThe OGC has four operational units:\n\n=== Standards program (SP) === \nIn the OGC Standards Program the Technical Committee and Planning Committee<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ogc.org/projects/groups|title=Groups & Committees &#124; OGC|website=www.ogc.org}}</ref> work in a formal consensus process to arrive at approved (or \"adopted\") OGC\u00ae standards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ogc.org/standards|title=OGC\u00ae Standards and Supporting Documents &#124; OGC|website=www.ogc.org}}</ref> Learn about the standards that have been approved so far, and see the lists of products<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ogc.org/resource/products|title=Certified and Implementing Products &#124; OGC|website=www.ogc.org}}</ref> that implement these standards.\n=== Innovation Program (IP) ===\nA global, innovative, hands-on prototyping and testing program designed to accelerate interface development and validation, and bring interoperability to the market. Learn about the different initiatives<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ogc.org/projects/initiatives|title=Active OGC Initiatives &#124; OGC|website=www.ogc.org}}</ref> currently under way, how they are organized, and how you can participate.\n=== Compliance Program (CP) === \nThe OGC Compliance Program provides the resources, procedures, and policies for improving software implementations' compliance with OGC standards. The Compliance Program provides an online free testing facility<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cite.opengeospatial.org/teamengine/|title=TEAM Engine|website=cite.opengeospatial.org}}</ref>, a process<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ogc.org/compliance|title=Compliance Testing &#124; OGC|website=www.ogc.org}}</ref> for certification and branding of compliant products, and coordination of a vibrant community<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/opengeospatial/cite|title=opengeospatial/cite|website=GitHub}}</ref> that develops and supports test scripts. The Compliance Program also runs plugfests, which are short term events for increasing interoperability among vendors' products. \n=== Community and Outreach Program (COP) === \nThe OGC and its members offer resources to help technology developers and users take advantage of the OGC's open standards. Technical documents, training materials, test suites, reference implementations and other interoperability resources developed in OGC Interoperability Initiatives are available on our resources page.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://wwwdev.opengeospatial.org/resources |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-09-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005051654/http://wwwdev.opengeospatial.org/resources |archive-date=2017-10-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In addition, the OGC and its members support publications, workshops, seminars and conferences<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ogc.org/event|title=Events List - times on this page are GMT &#124; OGC|website=www.ogc.org}}</ref> to help technology developers, integrators and procurement managers introduce OGC plug and play capabilities into their architectures.\n\n==Membership==\nThe OGC is an open membership organization. The OGC offers a range of membership options for industry, government, academic, research and not-for-profit organizations interested in supporting the Consortium's global mission<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ogc.org/ogc/join|title=Membership Levels &#124; OGC|website=www.ogc.org}}</ref>\n\n==Collaboration==\nThe OGC has a close relationship with [[ISO/TC 211]] (Geographic Information/Geomatics). Volumes from the ISO 19100 series under development by this committee progressively replace the OGC abstract specification. Further, the OGC standards Web Map Service, GML, Web Feature Service, [[Observations and Measurements]], and Simple Features Access have become ISO standards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opengeospatial.org/pressroom/pressreleases/1374|title=OGC Web Feature Service Standard accepted as ISO Standard|year=2011}}</ref>\n\nThe OGC works with more than 20 international standards-bodies including [[W3C]], [[OASIS (organization)|OASIS]], [[Workflow Management Coalition|WfMC]], and the [[IETF]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://portal.opengeospatial.org/files/?artifact_id=6207&ei=haJwVY7ZOcfusAXb4oK4DA&usg=AFQjCNEKzXyIOXuYNii4cRrwGU6wfD4BgQ&sig2=41F6mU19BEdW_td2wCIrIQ&bvm=bv.94911696,d.b2w|title=OGC\u2019s Role in the Spatial Standards World}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[GeoTools]] \u2013 implements OGC standards as OGC releases them\n*[[Open Source Geospatial Foundation]] (OSGeo)\n*[[List of geographic information systems software]]\n*[[Comparison of geographic information systems software]]\n*[[OpenLayers]]\n*[[Semantic Sensor Web]]\n*[[Weather Information Exchange Model]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website}}\n\n{{OGC}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Open Geospatial Consortium| ]]\n[[Category:Earth sciences metadata conventions]]\n[[Category:Geographic information systems organizations]]\n", "name_user": "Dadasacks", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Open_Geospatial_Consortium"}
{"title_page": "Charles Parks Richardson", "text_new": "[[File:Dr. Charles Richardson.jpg|thumb|Dr. Ricardson in March 2020]]\n'''Charles Parks Richardson''' (born July 5, 1971) is an American physician, philanthropist and visionary serial inventor of life-saving biotechnologies, medical devices and pharmaceuticals he is best known for the development of  the left-ventricular assist device (LVAD), the right-ventricular assist device (RVAD) and the total implantable, electric Total Artificial Heart (TAH). \n\nDr. Richardson was also honored in 2014 with a Global Medical Award for his groundbreaking product design and development. He is also the current Founder of Cleveland Diabetes Care which mission is to improve lives through innovations in the care for and treatment of diabetes with the ultimate goal of eliminating diabetes worldwide. {{Infobox person\n| name               = Dr. Charles Parks Richardson\n| birth_date         = July 5, 1971\n| education          = Winston-Salem State University,  Moore School of Business\n}}\n\n== Education ==\nRichardson received a B.S. degree in chemistry from [[Winston-Salem State University]] in [[Winston-Salem, North Carolina]]. He has an M.D. degree from Central America Health Sciences University School of Medicine. He holds an MBA from the University of South Carolina's [[Darla Moore School of Business|Moore School of Business]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Charles Parks Richardson, M.D., MBA|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/Research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=215335923&privcapId=214647461 |website=bloomberg.com|accessdate=21 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nRichardson co-founded the company Cleveland Heart in January 2007. The company's medical technology focuses on total heart replacement and ventricular assist devices.<ref>{{cite web|title=Company Overview of Cleveland Heart, Inc.|url=http://www.investing.businessweek.wallst.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=215335923&privcapId=214647461&previousCapId=214647461&previousTitle=Cleveland%20Heart,%20Inc.|website=www.investing.businessweek.wallst.com|publisher=Business Week|accessdate=21 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nRichardson co-founded IntelliServices Inc. and was its CEO in January 2000. The company offers remote [[Electronic Medical Record|electronic medical records]]. Its product CareLink allowed medical providers to wireless monitor implanted medical devices via the Internet.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cleveland Heart Founder Dr. Charles Richardson Appointed to ReliantHeart Board of Directors|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSnGNX6JK7kg+1d8+GNW20131114|website=www.Reuters.com|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=21 April 2016|language=en-US}}</ref> The company was sold and is now owned by Medtronic.<ref>{{cite web|title=Medtronic MyCareLink Connect|url=https://eu.mycarelinkconnect.com/PatientInfo/|website=eu.mycarelinkconnect.com|publisher=Medtronic|accessdate=21 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Richardson founded TransWorld Med. He also serves as the company chairman.<ref>{{cite web|title=TransWorld Med Corporation|url=http://www.transworldmed.com/Management.htm|website=www.transworldmed.com|accessdate=22 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Richardson founded TransWorld Kidney Corporation.<ref>{{cite web|title=TRANSWORLD KIDNEY CORPORATION LEGAL \u2013  NorthCarolinaCorps \u2013 Company Profiles of North Carolina|url=http://www.northcarolinacorps.com/corp/76689.html|website=www.northcarolinacorps.com|publisher=North Carolina Corporations}}</ref>\n\nRichardson is founder and chairman of Cleveland Heart, a partnership between [[Cleveland Clinic]] <nowiki/>and TransWorld Med to develop mechanical cardiac circulatory assist devices and artificial hearts.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/charlotte/print-edition/2012/08/03/group-pumps-30-million-into-cleveland.html|title=Group pumps $30 million into Cleveland Heart plan - Charlotte Business Journal|newspaper=Charlotte Business Journal|access-date=2016-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==Inventions==\nRichardson created IntelliPhysician, a piece of software based on the same paperless principles as IntelliHeart, but handles a wider range of business-related processes, such as scheduling, accounts receivable, financial history, and billing. The software also processes insurance claim forms and gathers and stores patients\u2019 clinical data, including procedure and diagnosis history, email, hospital rounds information, and referring physician information.<ref>{{cite web|title=H-Quotient, Inc., Acquires Intelliservices, Inc.; More Than $0.40 Per Share Earnings Projected for 2003 |url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20030314005170/en/H-Quotient-Acquires-Intelliservices-0.40-Share-Earnings-Projected|website=www.businesswire.com|publisher=Business Wire|accessdate=21 April 2016}}</ref> The company behind IntelliPhysician was acquired in 2006 by H-Quotient Inc. of Vienna, VA for $7.6m<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wraltechwire.com/2002/12/16/sc-based-medical-software-firm-is-acquired-in-7-3m-deal/|title=SC-based Medical Software Firm Is Acquired in $7.3M Deal|date=2002-12-16|website=WRAL TechWire|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-16}}</ref>.\n\nOne of TransWorld Heart Corp.'s inventions is the Soul Mate<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.implantable-device.com/2011/12/26/transworlds-soul-mate-implantable-heart-transplant-rejection-monitor/|title=TransWorld\u2019s Soul Mate Implantable Heart Transplant Rejection Monitor|last=Prutchi|first=David|date=2011-12-27|website=The World of Implantable Devices|access-date=2019-04-16}}</ref>. This product is an implantable device that can replace routine post-transplant heart [[biopsies]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Thomas|first1=Jennifer|title=Startup finds its Soul Mate \u2013 Charlotte Business Journal|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/charlotte/stories/2009/04/20/story10.html?b=1240200000%255E1812860|newspaper=Charlotte Business Journal|accessdate=22 April 2016}}</ref> The Soul Mate was the first device to offer remote monitoring of congestive heat failure and allows physicians to track a patient's condition from home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/charlotte/print-edition/2012/03/23/cardiac-device-maker-to-launch-25m.html|title=Cardiac device maker TransWorld to launch $25M clinical trial - Charlotte Business Journal|website=Charlotte Business Journal|access-date=2016-04-22}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007 Richardson developed the SideKick, a system for real-time monitoring of a kidney after a transplant.<ref>{{cite web|title=TransWorld Kidney: SideKick|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_fhiz9xCFOk|website=YouTube|publisher=TransWorldKidney|accessdate=22 April 2016|date=22 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Other ==\n[[Cdiabetescare.com]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Richardson, Charles}}\n[[Category:University of South Carolina alumni]]\n[[Category:Winston-Salem State University alumni]]\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American health care chief executives]]\n", "text_old": "'''Charles Parks Richardson''' (born July 5, 1971) is an American entrepreneur, doctor, and inventor<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=60062ac0-605e-11e9-ba9c-2f59d2f24112&url=L3Jlc2VhcmNoL3N0b2Nrcy9wcml2YXRlL3BlcnNvbi5hc3A/cGVyc29uSWQ9MjE1MzM1OTIzJnByaXZjYXBJZD0yMTQ2NDc0NjE=|title=Bloomberg \u2013 Are you a robot?|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2019-04-16}}</ref>.\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Dr. Charles Parks Richardson\n| birth_date         = July 5, 1971\n| education          = Winston-Salem State University,  Moore School of Business\n}}\n\n== Education ==\nRichardson received a B.S. degree in chemistry from [[Winston-Salem State University]] in [[Winston-Salem, North Carolina]]. He has an M.D. degree from Central America Health Sciences University School of Medicine. He holds an MBA from the University of South Carolina's [[Darla Moore School of Business|Moore School of Business]].<re