} || {{y}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Ultron]] || ''Avengers: Age of Ultron'' || {{n}} || {{n}} || {{y}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Wreck-It Ralph]] || ''Wreck-It Ralph'' || {{y}} || {{y}} || {{y}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Yoda]] || ''Star Wars: The Clone Wars'' || {{n}} || {{n}} || {{y}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Yondu]] || ''Guardians of the Galaxy'' || {{n}} || {{y}} || {{y}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Star Wars Rebels#Crew of the Ghost|Zeb Orrelios]] || ''Star Wars Rebels'' || {{n}} || {{n}} || {{y}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Peter Pan|Peter Pan (Unreleased Prototype)]] || ''Peter Pan'' || {{n}} || {{n}} || {{n}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Spider-Gwen|Spider-Gwen (Unreleased Prototype)]] || ''Ultimate Spider-Man'' || {{n}} || {{n}} || {{n}}\n|}\n<small>\n{{note|PC|PC}} \u2013 Windows version only<br />\n{{note|Con|Con}} \u2013 Console versions ({{note|Mob|Mob}} and the discontinued mobile version) only; update download required\n</small>\n\n==Disney Toy Box==\nFollowing the cancellation of the series, it was announced that Disney would be launching a series of action figures based on the art style used in the games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.starwars.com/news/inside-the-new-disney-infinity-inspired-toybox-star-wars-figures|title=Inside the New Disney Infinity-Inspired Star Wars Toybox Figures|date=November 21, 2017|website=StarWars.com|accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nerdist.com/disney-toybox-star-wars-marvel-pixar/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=May 14, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180514142218/https://nerdist.com/disney-toybox-star-wars-marvel-pixar/ |archive-date=May 14, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nTo date, the following characters have been released or revealed:\n\n===Star Wars===\n* [[Rey (Star Wars)|Rey]]\n* [[Kylo Ren]]\n* [[First Order (Star Wars)|First Order]] [[Stormtrooper (Star Wars)|Stormtrooper]] \n* [[Stormtrooper (Star Wars)|TIE Fighter]]\n* [[Darth Vader]]\n* [[Luke Skywalker]]\n* [[Boba Fett]]\n* [[Princess Leia]]\n* [[Han Solo]]\n* [[Chewbacca]]\n* [[Yoda]]\n* [[Poe Dameron]]\n* Kylo Ren (''[[The Rise of Skywalker]]'' version)\n* Rey (''The Rise of Skywalker'' version)\n* Sith Trooper\n\n====Play sets====\n* [[C-3PO]] and [[R2-D2]]\n\n===Marvel===\n* [[Thor (Marvel Comics)|Thor]]\n* [[Hulk]] \n* [[Spider-Man]]\n* [[Iron Man]] \n* [[Black Panther (Marvel Comics)|Black Panther]]\n* [[Black Widow (Natalia Romanova)|Black Widow]]\n* [[Captain America]]\n* [[Star-Lord]]\n* [[Doctor Strange]]\n* [[Ant-Man (Scott Lang)|Ant-Man]]\n* [[Hope van Dyne#In other media|The Wasp]]\n* Gray Hulk\n* [[Thanos]]\n* [[Miles Morales]]\n* Iron Man (''[[Captain America: Civil War]]'' version)\n* [[Rocket Raccoon]] and [[Groot|Baby Groot]]\n* [[Carol Danvers|Captain Marvel]] and Goose\n* [[Wolverine (character)|Wolverine]]\n* Spider-Man \n\n====Play sets====\n* Spider-Man with [[Spider-Mobile]]\n* [[Iron Man's armor|Hulkbuster]] and Hulk\n* [[Captain America: The Winter Soldier|Stealth suit Captain America]] and [[Bucky Barnes|Winter Soldier]] with Avengers motorcycle\n* Thor, [[War Machine]], [[Hawkeye (Clint Barton)|Hawkeye]], Black Widow, astral Doctor Strange and Hulk\n\n===Pixar===\n* [[Sheriff Woody|Woody]] (''[[Toy Story]]'')\n* [[Buzz Lightyear]] (''[[Toy Story]]'') \n* [[Jessie (Toy Story)|Jessie]] (''[[Toy Story]]'')\n* [[List of Toy Story characters|Bullseye]] (''[[Toy Story]]'')\n* [[Mr. Incredible]] and [[Jack-Jack]] (fire)  (''[[The Incredibles]]'')\n* [[Elastigirl]] and Jack-Jack (normal) (''[[The Incredibles]]'')\n* [[Violet Parr|Violet]] and Jack-Jack (monster) (''[[The Incredibles]]'')\n* [[Dash Parr|Dash]], Jack-Jack (metal) and [[Edna Mode]] (''[[The Incredibles]]'') \n* [[Frozone]] (''[[The Incredibles]]'')\n\n===Disney===\n* [[Mickey Mouse]]\n* [[Pluto (Disney)|Pluto]]\n* [[Minnie Mouse]]\n* [[Figaro (Disney)|Figaro]]\n* [[Jack Skellington]] and [[Zero]] (''[[The Nightmare Before Christmas]]'') \n* [[Hiro Takachiho|Hiro Hamada]]\n* [[Baymax]]\n* [[Moana (2016 film)|Moana]]\n* [[Moana (2016 film)|Maui]]\n* [[Wreck-It Ralph]]\n* [[Vanellope Von Schweetz]]\n* [[Stitch (Disney)|Stitch]]\n* [[Aladdin (Disney character)|Aladdin]]\n* [[Genie (Disney)|Genie]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://infinity.disney.com}}\n\n{{Disney Infinity}}\n{{DisneyConsumer}}\n{{Disney franchises}}\n{{Marvel Video Game Crossovers}}\n\n[[Category:Video game franchises]]\n[[Category:Disney video games]]\n[[Category:Action-adventure games]]\n[[Category:Open world video games]]\n[[Category:Superhero video games]]\n[[Category:Disney Interactive franchises]]\n[[Category:Crossover video games]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises introduced in 2013]]\n[[Category:Toys-to-life games]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the video game series|the video game|Disney Infinity (video game)}}\n{{Short description|Toys-to-life sandbox video game series that ran from 2013 to 2016}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox VG series\n| title          = Disney Infinity\n| creator        =\n| image          = File:Disney Infinity logo.jpg\n| caption        = \n| developer      = [[Avalanche Software]]\n| publisher      = [[Disney Interactive Studios]]\n| platforms      = [[Xbox 360]], [[Nintendo 3DS]], [[Wii]], [[Wii U]], [[PlayStation 3]], [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Xbox One]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[PlayStation Vita]], [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[Apple TV]]\n| genre          = [[Action-adventure game|Action-adventure]]<br/>[[nonlinear gameplay|Sandbox]]<br/>[[Toys-to-life]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/herocomplex/la-et-hc-the-player-e3-toys-to-life-20150613-story.html#page=1|title=Toys-to-life gaming at E3 is set to land big, but it's not all child's play|first=Todd|last=Martens|date=June 13, 2015|website=Latimes.com|accessdate=December 29, 2017}}</ref>\n| first release version = ''[[Disney Infinity (video game)|Disney Infinity]]''\n| first release date = {{start date|2013|8|18}}\n| latest release version = ''[[Disney Infinity 3.0]]''\n| latest release date =  {{start date|2015|8|30}}\n}}\n\n'''''Disney Infinity''''' is an [[action-adventure game|action-adventure]] [[nonlinear gameplay|sandbox]] [[toys-to-life]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/herocomplex/la-et-hc-the-player-e3-toys-to-life-20150613-story.html#page=1|title=Toys-to-life gaming at E3 is set to land big, but it's not all child's play|first=Todd|last=Martens|work=LA Times|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/05/04/toys-to-life-are-gamings-hottest-selling-accessory-of-2015|title=Toys-To-Life Are Gaming's Hottest-selling Accessory of 2015|first=Katie|last=Williams|work=[[IGN]]|date=May 4, 2015|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> video game series developed by [[Avalanche Software]]. The setting of the series is a giant customizable universe of imagination, known as the Toy Box, populated with toy versions of iconic [[List of Disney animated universe characters|Disney]], [[List of Pixar characters|Pixar]], [[List of Marvel Comics characters|Marvel]] and ''[[List of Star Wars characters|Star Wars]]'' characters.\n\nAs Avalanche Software was closed down on May 11, 2016, Disney announced that the franchise would be retired.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/5/10/11652866/disney-infinity-ending|title=Disney is ending its Infinity video game line, shutting down Avalanche Software|date=May 11, 2016|accessdate=May 11, 2016}}</ref> However, \"Gold Editions\" of the three games in the series were released for [[Microsoft Windows]] (via [[Steam (service)|Steam]]) on December 9, 2016, which contain all the existing released figures and playset contents up to and including the third game's ''[[Zootopia]]'' figures.\n\n==Games==\nThe first game, ''[[Disney Infinity (video game)|Disney Infinity]]'', was released on August 18, 2013 for [[Xbox 360]], [[Nintendo 3DS]], [[Wii]], [[PlayStation 3]], [[Wii U]], [[Microsoft Windows]] and [[iOS]]. The second game, ''[[Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes]]'', was released on September 23, 2014 for [[Wii U]], [[PlayStation 3]], [[Xbox 360]], [[Xbox One]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[PlayStation Vita]], [[iOS]], and [[Microsoft Windows]]. The third game, ''[[Disney Infinity 3.0]]'', was released on August 29, 2015 for [[PlayStation 4]], [[PlayStation 3]], [[Xbox 360]], [[Xbox One]], [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Wii U]], [[iOS]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2015/05/05/june-cover-revealed-disney-infinity-3-0.aspx?|title=June Cover Revealed \u2013 Disney Infinity 3.0|first=Jeff|last=Cork|work=[[Game Informer]]|date=May 5, 2015|accessdate=May 6, 2015}}</ref> The series was discontinued on May 10, 2016, due to Avalanche Software's closure, despite some sources stating that there were some major plans in place to keep the series alive, and the presence of numerous new characters and playsets previously planned.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iheartinfinity.com/disney-infinitys-ambitious-plans-future-cancelled/|title=Disney Infinity's Ambitious Plans For The Future (before it was cancelled...) -|date=May 13, 2016|website=Iheartinfinity.com|accessdate=December 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Gameplay==\n''[[Disney Infinity (video game)|Disney Infinity]]'' games are [[action-adventure game]]s with physical toys, open-world creation and story-driven gameplay. Characters, playsets and other features are brought into the game using figurines and discs with the included Infinity Base. With the exception of non-human characters, such as those from the ''[[Cars (franchise)|Cars]]'' series, each character has a double jump (unless in a vehicle) and a default set of attacks, as well as a unique ability. For example, [[List of Monsters, Inc. characters#James P. \"Sulley\" Sullivan|Sulley]] and [[Jack Skellington]] can roar to scare others, while [[Violet Parr|Violet]] and [[Randall Boggs|Randall]] can turn invisible. There are two main modes in this game: Play Set<ref name=DisneyInfinityPlaysets/> and Toy Box.<ref name=\"2modes\">{{cite web|last=Nichols|first=Scott|title=Disney Infinity preview: Skylanders challenger not the usual toy story|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/gaming/news/a451638/disney-infinity-preview-skylanders-challenger-not-the-usual-toy-story.html|publisher=Digital Spy|accessdate=21 January 2013|date=18 January 2013}}</ref> Each playset is essentially a self-contained world with its own gameplay, based on a specific film or series with recognizable characters and storylines. Characters from one world cannot enter into another world, but players can put any characters together in Toy Box mode. Toy Box is a sandbox mode that players can fully customize and explore.\n\n===Play Set mode===\nThere are a number of playsets available in the series, which are accessed via placing the relevant playset piece onto the Infinity Base and are based upon several intellectual property franchises. These playsets include:\n;''Disney Infinity 1.0''\n*''[[Pirates of the Caribbean]]''\n*''[[Monsters University]]''\n*''[[The Incredibles]]''\n*''[[Cars (franchise)|Cars]]'' \n*''[[The Lone Ranger (2013 film)|The Lone Ranger]]'' \n*''[[Toy Story (franchise)|Toy Story]] In Space'' \n\n''Disney Infinity 2.0 ''\n*''[[Avengers Assemble (TV series)|The Avengers]]''\n*''[[Ultimate Spider-Man (TV series)|Spider-Man]]''\n*''[[Guardians of the Galaxy (film)|Guardians of the Galaxy]]''\n\n''Disney Infinity 3.0''\n*''[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (2008 TV series)|Star Wars: Twilight of the Republic]]''\n*''[[Star Wars|Star Wars: Rise Against the Empire]]'' \n*''[[Star Wars: The Force Awakens]]''\n*''[[Inside Out (2015 film)|Inside Out]]''\n*''[[Finding Dory]]''\n*''[[Marvel Comics|Marvel Battlegrounds]]''\n\n\nThese playsets have their own unique campaign, which can be played with up to two players. However, all characters from a specific franchise can only play in their respective playset (for example, [[Mr. Incredible]] can't be used in the ''Pirates of the Caribbean'' playset), meaning two figures from the same series are required to play a playset in split-screen multiplayer. However, ''Marvel'', (except ''Marvel Battlegrounds'') and ''Star Wars'' playsets feature collectable \"Crossover/Champion coins\", which enable the use of certain characters from different playsets.<ref name=DisneyInfinityPlaysets>{{cite web | url=http://www.disneyinfinityfigures.com/disney-infinity-play-set-list | title=Disney INFINITY Playsets | publisher=Disney INFINITY Figures | date=29 May 2013 | access-date=29 May 2013 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130618233503/http://disneyinfinityfigures.com/disney-infinity-play-set-list | archive-date=June 18, 2013 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> Playing through a playset unlocks objects and vehicles that can be used in the Toy Box mode.\n\n===Toy Box mode===\nToy Box mode<ref name=DisneyInfinityToyBoxMode>{{cite web |url=http://www.iheartinfinity.com/disney-infinity-toy-box-mode | title=Disney Infinity Toy Box Mode | publisher=Disney Infinity | date=29 May 2013 | accessdate=29 May 2013}}</ref> allows players to create their own game in an open-world arena. Players can mix and match everything that is unlocked within each of the playsets including characters, weapons and gadgets. By unlocking new content in the ''Disney Infinity'' playsets, players are able to build their own worlds and essentially create their own game.<ref name=\"DisneyInfinityToyBoxMode\" /> There are various \"adventures\" in this mode, which help teach the player how to use the mode's tools. Players can also earn \"spins\" by playing through playsets or leveling up their characters, which can be used to unlock additional items. The mode supports online multiplayer, in which players can play around with items that only the other player has, albeit only during that session.\n\nA portable Toy Box became available in late 2013, exclusively for the [[iPad]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ca.ign.com/articles/2013/08/14/disney-infinity-goes-mobile|title=Disney Infinity Goes Mobile|last=Butts|first=Steve|date=August 14, 2013|accessdate=August 20, 2013|publisher=IGN}}</ref> A version of the Toy Box is also available for [[Microsoft Windows]]. These versions of the Toy Box utilize the web codes included with each ''Disney Infinity'' character.\n\n===Physical elements===\nThe ''Infinity Base''<ref name=\"dailymail\">{{cite web|title=Disney launches Infinity video game that costs more than an iPad Mini|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sciencetech/article-2263309/Disney-Infinity-video-game-costs-iPad-Mini--Infinity-base-characters-sold-separately.html|publisher=Daily Mail|accessdate=January 17, 2013|date=January 16, 2013}}</ref> has two round spots to place figurines, and a hexagonal spot to place world discs. When the figurines are placed on the ''Infinity Base'', the characters are imported into the game, while world discs unlock Play Sets.<ref name=\"2modes\" />\n\nPower Discs are discs that can be placed on the Infinity Base along with their characters to add new elements to the game. Players can use up to three environment enhancements (Hexagonal Power Discs) that can only be used in the Toy Box mode and up to two character enhancements (Circular Power Discs) per character. The environment enhancements can alter the terrain, change the background \"sky,\" add new vehicles or add new weapons. The character enhancements will alter things about the character such as damage done, replenish health, allow for faster experience gain for leveling and so on. One Power Disc is included with the Starter Pack while additional discs are sold in blind bags each containing two discs.<ref name=disneyinfinityfigures>{{cite web | url=http://www.disneyinfinityfigures.com/index.php/disney-infinity-power-discs-to-collect | title=Disney INFINITY Figures \u2014 Power Discs | publisher=Disney Infinity Figures | date=24 April 2013 | access-date=24 April 2013 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130420094219/http://disneyinfinityfigures.com/index.php/disney-infinity-power-discs-to-collect | archive-date=April 20, 2013 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Characters==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n<!--Please allow only ONE franchise per character.-->\n!Character!!Franchise!!''[[Disney Infinity (video game)|Disney Infinity]]''!!''[[Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes]]''!!''[[Disney Infinity 3.0]]''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Perry the Platypus|Agent P]] || ''[[Phineas and Ferb]]'' || {{y}} || {{y}} || {{y}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Ahsoka Tano]] || ''[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (2008 TV series)|Star Wars: The Clone Wars]]'' || {{n}} || {{n}} || {{y}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Aladdin (Disney character)|Aladdin]] || ''[[Aladdin (Disney franchise)|Aladdin]]'' || {{n}} || {{y}} || {{y}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Alice (Alice's Adventures in Wonderland)|Alice Kingsleigh]] || ''[[Alice Through the Looking Glass (2016 film)|Alice Through the Looking Glass]]'' || {{n}} || {{n}} || {{y}}{{ref|Con|Con}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Darth Vader|Anakin Skywalker]] || ''Star Wars: The Clone Wars'' || {{n}} || {{n}} || {{y}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Anger]] || ''[[Inside Out (2015 film)|Inside Out]]'' || {{n}} || {{n}} || {{y}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Anna (Frozen)|Anna]] || ''[[Frozen (franchise)|Frozen]]'' || {{y}} || {{y}} || {{y}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Ant-Man (Scott Lang)|Ant-Man]] || ''[[Captain America: Civil War]]'' || {{n}} || {{n}} || {{y}}{{ref|Con|Con}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Baloo]] || ''[[The Jungle Book (1967 film)|The Jungle Book]]'' || {{n}} || {{n}} || {{y}}{{ref|Con|Con}}{{ref|Mob|Mob}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Hector Barb